She flipped to an empty page and wrote down the date. Then she wrote below it: "5/11/648-12/13/648".
"Are you looking back on the past?" Avery asked, looking at the old notebook. Carly nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's only a few days until Christmas."
Carly tapped twice on the lantern, meaning "no." As expected by Avery, the Ice King never allowed Carly to leave his castle because she was seen as a "defect" in his eyes. Carly was born deaf and was the only girl in the family; all the other children were boys.
So was Avery, in their own unique way. When Avery came out as non-binary, the world seemed to change too. As punishment for being different, Avery was assigned most of their time to work alone.
They were also forced to be the princess's servant. But they didn't mind because they had a friend.
"Your birthday is approaching soon, right?" Avery asked, remembering that it would be the princess's birthday in just a few days. Carly nodded, a hint of sadness flashing in her light blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" Avery asked, recalling how Carly had answered this question last time.
No. Carly tapped the table. Avery knew it was a difficult topic for Carly to bring up. On that very day, she was confined to this room while her mother was executed. When the incident occurred, Avery was still an infant, but TA remembered the anger of the servants and citizens. TA heard that Queen Elvena was a good queen who could even predict future events.
"So... what do you want to do?" Avery asked. Carly looked up at Avery, excitement evident on her face. She handed Avery a piece of paper. However, when he bent down to look at it...
6 inches x 6 inches canvas
White, shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
A easel
"Do you want me to get these things for you?" Avery turned to the silent princess, who kept tapping her horsetail bun back and forth. "Is that right?" When she saw this usually quiet princess so enthusiastic about something, she couldn't help but giggle. This was the first time she had wanted something outside her room, and it wasn't related to books.
"Okay! See you later?" Avery said, standing up and walking through the mess of papers and notebooks.
Carly nodded and continued to curl up in her thick blanket, revisiting her memories.
TA stepped out of the room, feeling relieved that the princess was finally willing to try new things and had made requests outside her ability (such as paint).
TA passed through the hall again, trying not to pay attention to the whispers of the maids.
"I heard she's possessed by Queen Elvena, so she always goes to that room."
"I heard she eats children in that room."
"Does she look like a man? Is that normal?"
TA couldn't bear to hear any more and had to cover their ears. TA went to the royal painter's room, which is in the east wing, the second door on the left.
Avery approached the door, which, like Carly's, was beautifully decorated. The door featured a white dragon, one of the six original dragons said to have created the Frostland kingdom. It's no surprise that the painter likes history and has painted the white dragon on the door.
TA opened the door, expecting everything to be as usual—paints, pencils, and papers scattered everywhere, frames covering every inch of the walls. But the scene inside was completely different. The room was clean, with a red velvet backdrop and a chair. Sitting on the chair was Prince Aquilo, who was painting a portrait.
"Oh, good morning, Avery! Want to see the portrait of your future king?" Aquilo asked, winking at Avery.
"Sorry, Your Highness," she replied, beginning to search for what Princess Carly wanted. "I'm just here to get some art supplies."
"Little one, are you leaving so soon?" Aquaro asked, "But I wanted to see you again!"
"I don't want to." Avery found the art supplies on the list and put them in a box. "And I'm not a girl either."
The prince didn't take her seriously. "Oh, dearie, you know it's just a phase! Once you grow up, it'll be fine!" he mumbled.
"I have to go." She said, feeling uncomfortable as the prince continued talking. She recalled all the negative comments people had made about her gender identity. I really want to get away from him.
"So soon to leave?" The prince appeared at the door instantly, ignoring the cries of the royal painter.
"This is not how a future king should behave!" she shouted loudly.
"No one will know. People won't believe him if the painter values his life, and he wouldn't say anything reckless." The prince glanced at the painter, then leaned close to Avery. "How about a date?" she trembled in fear. Of course, she had heard many threats before, but none from the prince, let alone this future king.
"Do you know what 'no' means?" she angrily demanded, pushing the prince away.
"No." Aquilo smiled in response. This prince who could have anything naturally didn't know what 'no' meant.
Avery rolled his eyes. "Why do you want to date me out of all people? How many suitors do you have? A hundred?"
He laughed and interrupted, "To be precise, over five hundred." He shook his hair, swaying in the cold wind.
"See! Why me? I'm just a bane to the palace." They crossed their arms.
"You're the most beautiful girl I've ever seen." Aquillo placed a finger under Avery's chin, forcing him to look up at him.
